So like 4 or 5 years ago, i helped a stranger online financially, and we still text each other out of the blue checking in on each other.

Not to deny the people who have been very good to me. I love them. But I fail often to keep them close.

Sometimes I look back at my various relationships with friends, family, lovers (I dunno a better term), and it is a wonder that I let myself trust anyone.

Mainly had to write this as it's been knocking around in my head. I doubt anyone could convince me this is a good (meaning moral) business model for games.

In games, I don't understand it. No one was crying out to own digital items using their bank accounts. Even if they were, they don't work like a universal wallet. Someone read Ready Player One and thought that's how the world should be. Christ on a bike.

Whilst there is an argument for new technology needing investment for it to be adopted, crypto & NFTs are almost definitely a niche market unless we as people are forced to use it in our everyday lives (welcome to unending security problems if that happens)

It is an industry losing money in the extreme compared to its investment. And it's not an infrastructure problem, in my mind, it's the lack of use or any need for it. Most investment is about enforcing value through speculation. We have to believe it has value to give it value.

Anyone who has seen them should be scared as hell, it's unregulated, unequal, predatory and creates exploitative work.
And that's only if they work as intended. Right now, they are also security nightmares, with viruses and scams aplenty, extremely volatile prices &investment.
Tldr: imagine an MMO market place but using your own money.

I got slightly obsessed with researching blockchain/NFT games over the last week and I can say with little doubt, they don't improve games. They are what you have likely already heard, an artificial scarcity business model which doesn't give 'ownership' over anything really.

From about 8 to 17, I had some sort of bully. I had told several people in school, nothing got done. Things actually got worse. So I stopped telling people. But the pressure built up.
The lies were palatable alternatives to the boring reality. Stupidly.

I didn't realise I had trauma from being bullied for a decade. Instead I copied by lying about dramatic gangland warfare I was part of, because it was easy to admit the lie then the truth & say this is why I'm in pain and not be questioned for it.

I still won't come out to my parents directly unless I have to. I don't care what they think of me, but the last thing I need are more potentially barbed words or comments. It's all very difficult when it need not be. We should just be able to live as is.

Probably one of the weirdest ways I would try to 'pass' being neurotypical, untraumatised &/or straight was lying. Okay not lysing, but the kind of lies. I fabricated whole branches of my life on the fly. Because an OTT fantasy was easier to believe than a boring reality.

Sexuality is actually not hard to figure out after a time.
What IS difficult is navigating the various parts of societies out there to know if you're safe in expressing yourself. Not just safe, but understood, loved, acknowledged as being you.

Then again maybe it's not queer media. Maybe it's straight people who did some decent representation of queer people. It feels more than that, but it doesn't really focus on some of the queer experience I expected.
Idk, I want to recommend it but then I get a hurt feeling.

Spoilers:
I genuinely didn't think we'd see a "bury your gays" ending, but here we are.
There's this hope for things to get better but so many characters were hurting by the end of the season, I just feel so sad & hurt.
This is why I avoid queer media, I get too close.

Saying that the main quest is vastly inferior to the side quests so far in quality. I get people want/need a central story thread but I really do think open world's could benefit from a complete narrative shakeup sometimes. DL2 just doesn't grab with its clich√©d main story.

The scriptwriting is terrible though. I don't mean to shit on it, it's mostly functional, but the lack of personality and goals of characters really shows when the voice actors fail to do anything with the lines.
The world holding is nice enough too, the inhabited zones feel appropriate. Random NPCs, friendly and foe, appearing in the wild feels good to get that lived in world.

Actual city movement is really nice. The level designers here really did a great job with this first city area. Almost always something to climb, feels like the playground it is.
Shame it takes ages to get a lot of the parkour moves really.

The orange dialogue choices are meant to be 'decision' moments, a nice touch cos there's enough of them that it's not corridored into feeling like its just end of path choices.
I think the choices don't matter, but the presentation makes them feel like they do. Nice work there.

The tutorial quest when you're in the city feels like 
It's established the PC is very knowledgeable about travelling & staying alive in this dangerous world, but the NPC still tells you how to craft, sneak, all the obvious stuff they know.
Not really the best interaction.

Narratively it's pretty bad. PC talks to themselves constantly about what's right infront of them. Real blank slate stuff.
There's a whole bit where the PC goes to bed, has a flashback dream of bad past, then wakes up to follow remnants of bad past, then hopeful music. Unearned.

There's so many indications that Dying Light 2 went through dev hell. The opening really could've done with a whole redesign & rewrite for a start. It feels lost, no sense of identity off the bat. Also doesn't introduce core mechanics or gameplay loop.
